{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492712"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:42:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:42:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1137"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1137"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.06,0.55,0.09,0.23,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1137"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"23673"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1137","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1137"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1137"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"11978"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"460"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"721"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30947"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"23673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/23673"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 64-year-old woman of Afghanistan origin presents with a one day history of colicky lower abdominal pain associated with vomiting and diarrhoea. She does not speak any English and the history is limited. Her blood pressure is 110/70 mmHg, pulse 90/min and temperature 37.2C. Her abdomen is slightly distended and soft to palpation. A plain abdominal radiograph is performed. (Image)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for the calcification?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Faecoliths","Gallstones","Hydatid disease","Kidney stones","Tuberculosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAll the conditions listed could show up on a plain abdominal radiograph as an area of calcification. From their position alone, the most likely explanation for these areas of calcification are \u003Cstrong\u003Egallstones\u003C/strong\u003E. Gallstones are common - with perhaps some 30% of woman developing such stones over their lifetime. Most of these individuals will never have any stone-related symptoms. This patient\u0027s current symptoms do not appear to be biliary in origin and the stones are almost certainly an incidental finding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOnly around 20% of gallstones are visible on plain film. The more common cholesterol-rich stones are typically radiolucent, with stones that are higher in bilurubin content (mixed or pigment stones) being radio-opaque.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Most gallstones remain asymptomatic and as such, can be found incidentally on imaging."],"references":["Loo JT, Duddalwar V, Chen FK et al. Abdominal radiograph pearls and pitfalls for the emergency department radiologist: a pictorial review. Abdom Radiol 2017; 42:987-1019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"11978"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1137"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15324"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15324","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15324"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/89769a74-4bc2-430a-88ca-03dc5314fc2c.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/89769a74-4bc2-430a-88ca-03dc5314fc2c.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":561,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"11978","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/11978"},"attr